Based on the provided search results and general understanding, here is the difference between "roasting" and "humiliation" in a Gujarati context: 
1. Roasting (રમુજી રીતે ટીકા કરવી/શેકવું - Ramuji rite tika karvi/Shekvu) 

• Meaning: Roasting is the act of teasing, mocking, or criticizing someone in a humorous, witty, or light-hearted manner. 
• Purpose: It is generally done for entertainment, often among friends, to highlight someone's flaws in a funny way without the intent to cause deep pain. 
• Gujarati Context: In Gujarati, this can be understood as "ખેંચવી" (Khenchvi) or "મજાક કરવી" (Majak karvi). It is often seen as harmless fun, similar to a "roast comedy" show. [1]  

2. Humiliation (અપમાન/તેજોવધ/હલકું પાડવું - Apman/Tejovadh/Halku padvu) 

• Meaning: Humiliation is a much more severe action that involves deeply shaming, embarrassing, or degrading someone, causing a significant loss of self-respect or face. 
• Purpose: The intent is often malicious or results in making the person feel small, stupid, or rejected. It is a form of disrespect. 
• Gujarati Terms: 

	• અપમાન (Apman): Insult. 
	• તેજોવધ (Tejovadh): To damage someone's reputation or pride. 
	• હલકું પાડવું (Halku padvu): To lower someone's status or make them feel small. 
	• બેઈજ્જત (Beijjat): Disrespect/Dishonor. [3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]  

Key Differences in Gujarati Context 

| Feature [9, 10, 11, 12, 13] | Roasting (ટીકા/મજાક) | Humiliation (અપમાન)  |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Intent | Humorous, Friendly | Malicious, Hurtful  |
| Result | Laughter, Embarrassment (mild) | Shame, Pain, Degradation  |
| Relationship | Usually between friends/equals | Often a power dynamic  |
| Context | "એની ખેંચી" (Teased him/her) | "તેનું અપમાન કર્યું" (Insulted him/her)  |

Summary: Roasting is playful, while humiliation is harmful. In Gujarati, you would call roasting "મજાક-મસ્તી" (Majak-masti), while humiliation is known as "અપમાનિત કરવું" (Apmanit karvu) or "ગર્વ ઉતારવો" (Garv utarvo). [4, 9, 14]  

